{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "SoilWaterFlux",
        "description": "Soil water flux at the interface between two adjacent soil layers, computed from Darcy's law with the Zeng and Decker (2009) equilibrium-potential correction (Oleson et al. 2010, CLM4 Tech Note Eq. 5.88). q = -k_interface * ((ψ_upper - ψ_lower) + (ψ_E_lower - ψ_E_upper)) / (z_lower - z_upper), positive upward. Migrated from UrbanCanopy.jl@9200edd4 src/hydrology.jl:471 (`SoilWaterFlux` @component). Observed-only: the seven inputs are parameters and q is given by a single algebraic equation.",
        "tags": [
            "urban_canopy",
            "hydrology",
            "soil",
            "darcy",
            "observed-only",
            "clmu"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-12T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "UrbanCanopy.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-88at)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Oleson, K. W., et al. (2010). Technical Description of version 4.0 of the Community Land Model (CLM). NCAR Technical Note NCAR/TN-478+STR. Chapter 5 (Soil Water), Section 5.3.2 (Soil Water Fluxes), Eqs. 5.87-5.88, p. 135."
            },
            {
                "citation": "Zeng, X., and M. Decker (2009). Improving the numerical solution of soil moisture-based Richards equation for land models with a deep or shallow water table. Journal of Hydrometeorology, 10(1), 308-319."
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "SoilWaterFlux": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: UrbanCanopy.jl@9200edd4f15609f20339d3a7d104de8064544310:src/hydrology.jl:471\nUpstream `SoilWaterFlux` is an MTK `@component` whose seven inputs (k_interface, ψ_upper, ψ_lower, ψ_E_upper, ψ_E_lower, z_upper, z_lower) are `@parameters` and whose single output (q) is a time-indexed `@variable` with one algebraic equation (Eq. 5.88, no derivative). Identical structure preserved here.\n\nUnicode parameter names ψ_upper, ψ_lower, ψ_E_upper, ψ_E_lower are preserved from upstream — sibling files in this directory (soil_water_content_calc.esm, water_table_depth.esm, interface_hydraulic_conductivity.esm) and components/urban_canopy/temps/freezing_point_depression.esm already established that unicode identifiers are the rig convention for new urban_canopy migrations and the canonical Python runner accepts them.\n\nThe upstream component has no `@constants` block and no defaults in `@parameters`. Defaults here are taken from the upstream Equation Verification test (UrbanCanopy.jl test/hydrology_test.jl:690, equilibrium case): k_interface=1.0e-5 m/s, ψ_upper=-0.5 m, ψ_lower=-1.0 m, ψ_E_upper=-0.3 m, ψ_E_lower=-0.8 m, z_upper=0.1 m, z_lower=0.3 m → q = -1e-5 * ((-0.5-(-1.0)) + (-0.8-(-0.3))) / (0.3-0.1) = -1e-5 * (0.5 + (-0.5)) / 0.2 = 0 m/s. The default state is the canonical equilibrium for which the gravitational-equilibrium correction exactly cancels the matric-potential gradient — a useful default since any non-trivial perturbation surfaces a non-zero flux.\n\nEq. 5.88 form: q = -k[z_h] * [(ψ_i - ψ_{i+1}) + (ψ_{E,i+1} - ψ_{E,i})] / (z_{i+1} - z_i). The bracketed term is the *perturbation* of the matric potential from the local hydrostatic equilibrium (Zeng and Decker 2009) — ψ_E is the equilibrium matric potential at each layer node and ψ - ψ_E is the deviation that drives flux. Without the correction, gravitationally-induced equilibrium gradients would produce a spurious flux; with the correction, the flux vanishes when ψ_upper - ψ_lower = ψ_E_upper - ψ_E_lower (the default scenario).\n\nSign convention: q is positive *upward*. The leading minus sign is encoded in the AST via `{op: '*', args: [-1, k_interface, ...]}`, matching the convention established by sibling files (snow_compaction.esm uses `-1` as a literal first argument to the `*` op).\n\nObservability classification: this component is functionally observed-only — q is given by a single algebraic equation in the parameters (the `(t)` time index has no role since there is no derivative). Test scenarios use `time_span: [0, 1]` and sample at t=0 to mirror the convention used by the other observed-only ESM files in this directory (soil_water_content_calc.esm, water_table_depth.esm, interface_hydraulic_conductivity.esm).\n\nTolerance rationale (model-level rel=1e-9): observed-only algebraic system (no ODE integration); the equation is a chain of three subtractions, one addition, one multiplication (by -1 and k_interface), and one division — eight IEEE-754 float64 operations, worst-case roundoff ~8*ULP ≈ 1e-15. 1e-9 leaves comfortable headroom and is well below any plausible physical-discrimination scale on soil water fluxes (m/s, O(1e-6) for the saturated end and O(1e-12) for the dry end of CLMU soils; gradients across realistic layer separations of O(0.1 m) span ~6 orders of magnitude). Equilibrium / zero-flux tests assert `abs: 1e-15` since the upstream Julia test pins exactly that bound (Eq. 5.88 evaluates to a closed-form zero when the matric-potential perturbation vanishes)."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1.0e-9
            },
            "variables": {
                "k_interface": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 1.0e-5,
                    "description": "Hydraulic conductivity at the interface between adjacent layers (Oleson Eq. 5.88)"
                },
                "ψ_upper": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": -0.5,
                    "description": "Soil matric potential of the upper layer (negative by convention, SI m)"
                },
                "ψ_lower": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": -1.0,
                    "description": "Soil matric potential of the lower layer (negative by convention, SI m)"
                },
                "ψ_E_upper": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": -0.3,
                    "description": "Equilibrium matric potential of the upper layer (Zeng and Decker 2009 correction, SI m)"
                },
                "ψ_E_lower": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": -0.8,
                    "description": "Equilibrium matric potential of the lower layer (Zeng and Decker 2009 correction, SI m)"
                },
                "z_upper": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.1,
                    "description": "Node depth of the upper layer (positive downward from surface)"
                },
                "z_lower": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.3,
                    "description": "Node depth of the lower layer (positive downward from surface)"
                },
                "q": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "description": "Soil water flux at the interface (Oleson Eq. 5.88, positive upward)"
                }
            },
            "equations": [
                {
                    "lhs": "q",
                    "rhs": {
                        "op": "/",
                        "args": [
                            {
                                "op": "*",
                                "args": [
                                    -1,
                                    "k_interface",
                                    {
                                        "op": "+",
                                        "args": [
                                            { "op": "-", "args": ["ψ_upper", "ψ_lower"] },
                                            { "op": "-", "args": ["ψ_E_lower", "ψ_E_upper"] }
                                        ]
                                    }
                                ]
                            },
                            { "op": "-", "args": ["z_lower", "z_upper"] }
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tests": [
                {
                    "id": "equilibrium_zero_flux",
                    "description": "Canonical equilibrium case from upstream Equation Verification (UrbanCanopy.jl test/hydrology_test.jl:699): k_interface = 1e-5 m/s, ψ_upper = -0.5 m, ψ_lower = -1.0 m, ψ_E_upper = -0.3 m, ψ_E_lower = -0.8 m, z_upper = 0.1 m, z_lower = 0.3 m. The matric-potential gradient (ψ_upper - ψ_lower = 0.5 m) exactly cancels the equilibrium-potential gradient (ψ_E_lower - ψ_E_upper = -0.5 m), so the Zeng and Decker (2009) perturbation vanishes and q = 0 m/s. Verifies the equilibrium branch of Eq. 5.88 — the primary purpose of the equilibrium-potential correction.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "k_interface": 1.0e-5,
                        "ψ_upper": -0.5,
                        "ψ_lower": -1.0,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -0.3,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -0.8,
                        "z_upper": 0.1,
                        "z_lower": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "q", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.0, "tolerance": { "abs": 1.0e-15 } }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "non_zero_downward_flux",
                    "description": "Non-zero downward flux from upstream Equation Verification (UrbanCanopy.jl test/hydrology_test.jl:715): k_interface = 1e-5 m/s, ψ_upper = -0.2 m, ψ_lower = -0.5 m, ψ_E_upper = ψ_E_lower = -0.1 m (uniform equilibrium → no correction), z_upper = 0.1 m, z_lower = 0.3 m. The matric-potential perturbation drives flux: q = -1e-5 * ((-0.2 - (-0.5)) + 0) / 0.2 = -1e-5 * 0.3 / 0.2 = -1.5e-5 m/s (negative → downward, consistent with the upper layer being wetter / less negative ψ). Verifies the non-equilibrium branch of Eq. 5.88.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "k_interface": 1.0e-5,
                        "ψ_upper": -0.2,
                        "ψ_lower": -0.5,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -0.1,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -0.1,
                        "z_upper": 0.1,
                        "z_lower": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "q", "time": 0.0, "expected": -1.5e-5 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "upward_flux_dry_upper",
                    "description": "Upward flux: the lower layer is wetter (less negative ψ) than the upper layer, so soil water moves upward to relieve the matric-potential gradient (capillary rise). k_interface = 2e-6 m/s, ψ_upper = -1.5 m, ψ_lower = -0.5 m, uniform equilibrium ψ_E_* = -0.1 m, z_upper = 0.1 m, z_lower = 0.3 m. q = -2e-6 * ((-1.5 - (-0.5)) + 0) / 0.2 = -2e-6 * (-1.0) / 0.2 = +1.0e-5 m/s (positive → upward). Verifies the sign convention (positive upward) and an upward-driven flux.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "k_interface": 2.0e-6,
                        "ψ_upper": -1.5,
                        "ψ_lower": -0.5,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -0.1,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -0.1,
                        "z_upper": 0.1,
                        "z_lower": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "q", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.0e-5 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "pure_equilibrium_perturbation",
                    "description": "Pure equilibrium-perturbation flux: the matric potentials are uniform (ψ_upper = ψ_lower) so the actual gradient is zero, but the equilibrium potentials differ. q is driven entirely by the (ψ_E_lower - ψ_E_upper) term. k_interface = 1e-5 m/s, ψ_upper = ψ_lower = -0.5 m, ψ_E_upper = -0.4 m, ψ_E_lower = -0.6 m, z_upper = 0.1 m, z_lower = 0.3 m. q = -1e-5 * (0 + (-0.6 - (-0.4))) / 0.2 = -1e-5 * (-0.2) / 0.2 = +1.0e-5 m/s. Isolates the Zeng-Decker correction term and confirms its sign convention.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "k_interface": 1.0e-5,
                        "ψ_upper": -0.5,
                        "ψ_lower": -0.5,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -0.4,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -0.6,
                        "z_upper": 0.1,
                        "z_lower": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "q", "time": 0.0, "expected": 1.0e-5 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "wider_layer_separation",
                    "description": "Wider layer separation reduces the gradient and so reduces |q| at fixed potentials. Same matric and equilibrium potentials as `non_zero_downward_flux`, but z_lower = 1.1 m instead of 0.3 m so (z_lower - z_upper) = 1.0 m (5× larger). q = -1e-5 * 0.3 / 1.0 = -3.0e-6 m/s, i.e. 5× smaller magnitude than the canonical 0.3 m separation case. Exercises the 1/(z_lower - z_upper) dependence in Eq. 5.88.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "k_interface": 1.0e-5,
                        "ψ_upper": -0.2,
                        "ψ_lower": -0.5,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -0.1,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -0.1,
                        "z_upper": 0.1,
                        "z_lower": 1.1
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "q", "time": 0.0, "expected": -3.0e-6 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "high_conductivity_proportional",
                    "description": "Flux is linearly proportional to k_interface. With the same `non_zero_downward_flux` potentials and geometry but k_interface = 1e-4 m/s (10× larger), q = -1e-4 * 0.3 / 0.2 = -1.5e-4 m/s (10× larger magnitude). Exercises the linear k_interface scaling in Eq. 5.88 — important since k_interface itself varies over many orders of magnitude across the soil saturation range (~1e-12 to ~1e-5 m/s).",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "k_interface": 1.0e-4,
                        "ψ_upper": -0.2,
                        "ψ_lower": -0.5,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -0.1,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -0.1,
                        "z_upper": 0.1,
                        "z_lower": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "q", "time": 0.0, "expected": -1.5e-4 }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "zero_conductivity_zero_flux",
                    "description": "Zero hydraulic conductivity (e.g. fully frozen layer, k_interface → 0) blocks all flux regardless of the matric-potential gradient. k_interface = 0.0, all other parameters from the `non_zero_downward_flux` scenario. q = 0 * (anything) / (anything > 0) = 0 m/s. Verifies the k_interface = 0 limit of Eq. 5.88 — physically meaningful for frozen or impervious interfaces.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "k_interface": 0.0,
                        "ψ_upper": -0.2,
                        "ψ_lower": -0.5,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -0.1,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -0.1,
                        "z_upper": 0.1,
                        "z_lower": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "q", "time": 0.0, "expected": 0.0, "tolerance": { "abs": 1.0e-15 } }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "deep_soil_low_conductivity",
                    "description": "Deep soil column with low conductivity and a small matric-potential gradient — representative of a near-saturation interior layer pair. k_interface = 5e-8 m/s, ψ_upper = -2.0 m, ψ_lower = -2.1 m (small gradient), uniform equilibrium ψ_E_* = -1.0 m, z_upper = 1.5 m, z_lower = 2.0 m (deep interface, 0.5 m separation). q = -5e-8 * ((-2.0 - (-2.1)) + 0) / 0.5 = -5e-8 * 0.1 / 0.5 = -1.0e-8 m/s. Tests Eq. 5.88 at a small-magnitude operating point characteristic of the deep mineral-soil column.",
                    "parameter_overrides": {
                        "k_interface": 5.0e-8,
                        "ψ_upper": -2.0,
                        "ψ_lower": -2.1,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -1.0,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -1.0,
                        "z_upper": 1.5,
                        "z_lower": 2.0
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "assertions": [
                        { "variable": "q", "time": 0.0, "expected": -1.0e-8 }
                    ]
                }
            ],
            "examples": [
                {
                    "id": "q_vs_psi_upper",
                    "description": "Soil water flux vs. upper-layer matric potential at fixed lower-layer state and uniform equilibrium correction. Sweeping ψ_upper from -2.0 m (dry) to 0 m (saturated) at fixed ψ_lower = -0.5 m traces the linear Darcy response of Eq. 5.88: q is positive (upward) when ψ_upper < ψ_lower (capillary rise from wetter lower layer) and negative (downward) when ψ_upper > ψ_lower.",
                    "initial_state": {
                        "type": "per_variable",
                        "values": {}
                    },
                    "parameters": {
                        "k_interface": 1.0e-5,
                        "ψ_lower": -0.5,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -0.1,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -0.1,
                        "z_upper": 0.1,
                        "z_lower": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "ψ_upper",
                                "range": { "start": -2.0, "stop": 0.0, "count": 21, "scale": "linear" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "q_vs_psi_upper_line",
                            "type": "line",
                            "description": "q vs ψ_upper — linear Darcy response through the gradient zero-crossing at ψ_upper = ψ_lower.",
                            "x": { "variable": "ψ_upper", "label": "ψ_upper (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "q",       "label": "q (m/s, +upward)" }
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "q_vs_psi_upper_and_k",
                    "description": "Joint sweep over ψ_upper and k_interface — surfaces the iso-q contours of Eq. 5.88. Higher k_interface amplifies the same matric-potential gradient into proportionally larger fluxes; the iso-q lines are hyperbolae in (ψ_upper, k_interface) space at fixed denominator.",
                    "initial_state": {
                        "type": "per_variable",
                        "values": {}
                    },
                    "parameters": {
                        "ψ_lower": -0.5,
                        "ψ_E_upper": -0.1,
                        "ψ_E_lower": -0.1,
                        "z_upper": 0.1,
                        "z_lower": 0.3
                    },
                    "time_span": { "start": 0.0, "end": 1.0 },
                    "parameter_sweep": {
                        "type": "cartesian",
                        "dimensions": [
                            {
                                "parameter": "ψ_upper",
                                "range": { "start": -2.0, "stop": 0.0, "count": 13, "scale": "linear" }
                            },
                            {
                                "parameter": "k_interface",
                                "range": { "start": 1.0e-7, "stop": 1.0e-4, "count": 10, "scale": "log" }
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    "plots": [
                        {
                            "id": "q_heatmap",
                            "type": "heatmap",
                            "description": "q as a function of upper-layer matric potential and hydraulic conductivity (log k axis).",
                            "x": { "variable": "ψ_upper",     "label": "ψ_upper (m)" },
                            "y": { "variable": "k_interface", "label": "k_interface (m/s, log scale)" },
                            "value": { "variable": "q", "reduce": "final" }
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        }
    }
}
